#!/usr/local/projects/routing/help/html_filter.pl
<h2 align=center>What is a route sheet?</h2>
At its heart, this concept is the same from distributor to distributor across all routes:
Present the driver with a list of stops including names, addresses, phone numbers (in the event
the person isn't there), and notes for delivery.
<ul>
    <li>Example route sheet as it would look <a href="sample_route_sheet.pdf">printed</a>.
	<p>As printed, printed route sheets include all of the information that was available with old route
	sheets used prior to computer routing.  They can be used as a simple replacement for the old sheets.
	In addition, the new sheet includes:
	<ul>
	    <li>A QR code on top which will point a smart phone browser to a web application which will
		stay resident for logging the position of the driver and notes for each stop.
	    <li>QR codes next to each patron which would point a smart phone GPS to that patron and
	        every subsequent stop.
	    <li>The phone number of the patron in case there are problems delivering.
	    <br>&nbsp;
	</ul>
    <li>Example route sheet as it would look <a href="sample_route_sheet.cgi">viewed on a browser</a> or
	in e-mail.
	<p>If viewed in e-mail:
	<ul>
	    <li>The top "take live" link takes the operator to the same web application the top QR code does
	        in the printed sheet.
	    <li>Each address next to a patron would point a smart phone GPS to that patron and
	        every subsequent stop.
	    <li>There is a link to the phone number of the patron in case there are problems delivering.
	    <br>&nbsp;
	</ul>
    </ul>

